  "text": "The diverse health outcomes associated with high aggression in the honey bee implicate a number of tissues including the brain as a regulator of behavior, the fat body, a metabolic tissue that is involved in immune response [CITATION_1] , and the midgut, which is involved in pesticide detoxification [CITATION_2] . Communication between peripheral, immune responsive tissues and the brain is characteristic of sickness behavior in vertebrates [CITATION_3] , but in the context of honey bee aggression, no study has evaluated tissues other than the brain to establish a role for peripheral systems in behavioral variation.",
